Detailed steps:

  1. Create a new Node.js project in the specified context:
```
mkdir C:\Users\user\AppData\Local\Temp\tmp_lhsmlzq
cd C:\Users\user\AppData\Local\Temp\tmp_lhsmlzq
npm init -y
```
  2. Install the required dependencies for the project:
```
npm install express body-parser
```
  3. Set up the server to run on port 3000:
```
touch app.js
nano app.js
```
In the `app.js` file, add the following code:
```
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');
const app = express();
app.use(bodyParser.json());
app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({ extended: true }));
app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server is running on port 3000');
});
```
This code sets up an Express server that listens on port 3000 and uses body-parser to parse the request body.
  4. Configure the API to run on the server:
```
touch api.js
nano api.js
```
In the `api.js` file, add the following code:
```
const express = require('express');
const app = express();
app.use(bodyParser.json());
app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({ extended: true }));
app.post('/api', (req, res) => {
  res.send('Hello World!');
});
app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server is running on port 3000');
});
```
This code sets up an Express API that listens on port 3000 and responds with "Hello World!" when a POST request is made to the `/api` endpoint.
  5. Test the server to ensure it is running correctly:
```
node app.js
node api.js
```
This will start the server on port 3000 and the API on port 3000.
Note that the Node.js version should be 14.x, which can be installed using the following command:
```
nvm install 14.x
```